&lt;p&gt;# Comments: 0&lt;/p&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48991134</guid><pubDate>Tue, 21 Jul 2026 12:02:43 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Show HN: ChatPanel, A Privacy-first AI Agent browser side panel</title><link>https://chatpanel.net/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;I needed an AI agent that understands my work better (meetings, notes, chats and lives where I access the web) and gives me flexibility to use the model of choice. So, I built this and I am a 100x engineer now.&lt;p&gt;A few features to highlight.&lt;p&gt;- You bring your own Agent (Codex, claude code etc) or local models or in-browser models or remote models
- A live meeting assistant. You got to try to this to see the power of it
- A local note taking app where AI Agents live
- Voice to Text (all local)
- NER and PII redaction before sending data to agents, models
- Search across your chats,  notes and meetings
- Try asking drawing stuff on excalidraw ot tldr draw in browser act mode
- in-built MCP hub you can add
- Bring your own CLI agent (pi, opencode etc)&lt;p&gt;Complete flexibility on which model, agent you want to send each message to while we don't track any data. Its Open source for you to validate all the privacy claims to build your trust&lt;p&gt;You just need the browser extension and associated npm packages to build the bridge between your AI agents/models and the extension. Give it a try.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Comments URL: &lt;a href="https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48991094"&gt;https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48991094&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Points: 1&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;# Comments: 0&lt;/p&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48991094</guid><pubDate>Tue, 21 Jul 2026 11:56:19 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Ask HN: Have you noticed convincing AI comments on Product Hunt?</title><link>https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48991063</link><description>&lt;p&gt;A few days ago, I launched my tool on Product Hunt for the first time. Although it didn't rank high, I received four comments and a few upvotes. I felt a small but genuine sense of accomplishment.
Naturally, I replied to each comment with care.
However, I later got curious about who left those comments and clicked on their X (Twitter) profile links. I was shocked by what I found... out of the four accounts, two were banned, and the other two were created within the last three months with zero posts.
Please note that what follows is just my speculation.
To me, their comments felt completely natural. They aligned well with my tool's description, and one even offered a genuinely useful feature suggestion.
But when I carefully re-examined the wording, I realized the phrases fit the typical output pattern of modern LLMs—that polite, articulate, and well-structured review template. They were very likely bots.
Of course, I cannot say for certain that they were AI bots.
Has anyone else experienced something similar on Product Hunt or other launch platforms? I'd love to hear your experiences.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
